    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. So you're saying the expansion of rights is basically the most important outcome of this doctrine. I'm just wondering, though—when critics say that this \"engine for expanding civil rights\" actually bypasses the democratic process and lets unelected judges make laws, isn't that a pretty significant flaw in the concept itself?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics are right that unelected judges making law is a flaw, but it is a necessary flaw because the democratic process often fails to protect vulnerable minorities from the \"tyranny of the majority.\" If we strictly followed the original text or relied solely on elected officials, we would have seen the systematic denial of rights for women, minorities, and the poor for much longer. Therefore, while judicial overreach is a risk, substantive due process remains the only reliable mechanism to correct democratic failures and ensure fundamental liberties are never lost to popular opinion.",
      "source": "target",
